Beijing’s natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wild animals to “settle” in the city - chinanews.com
2020-07-26 05:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The capital’s natural ecology continues to improve, attracting wild animals to “settle” in the city
More than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
News from our newspaper (Reporter Wang Bin) A reporter from the Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Landscaping Bureau that in recent years, as the capital’s natural ecological environment continues to improve, the types and numbers of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial spine wild animals inhabiting Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including national first-class protected animals such as brown horse chicken and black stork, as well as national second-class protected animals such as goral, whooper swan, gray crane and mandarin duck.
Whether it is planted into the urban forests in the second ring road or the small wetlands embedded in the buildings, it not only brings the wildness of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to “settle” in the city.
In midsummer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of vitality.
A raccoon was playing leisurely by the mountain stream, and two dog badgers were fighting with each other on the side.
Looking back, a wild boar couldn’t help the “thorn scratch” on its body, and was rubbing hard against the bark. According to Hu Qiaoli, Director of the Management Office of Songshan National Nature Reserve, as of the end of 2019, in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, there are living in this green sea, including the national first-class protected animal golden eagle and the national second-class protected animal spoon chicken and goral. Of the 178 species of wild animals in the city, nearly one-third of the city’s wild animal species can be seen here.
“In Songshan, wild animals are the real ‘owners’, and our staff can only be regarded as people’s ‘bodyguards’ at best.”
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the situation of wildlife in the reserve, there are more than 30 professional patrol team members every day to patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes, and there will be a “turning circle” every month. I walked almost the entire reserve in a whole day.
“During inspections, not only check and record the status of biodiversity, but also check the installation of artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install field infrared cameras and so on.”
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli introduced that with the continuous enrichment of biodiversity in the reserve in the past few years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the lens. Ocelots, raccoon and pig badgers have become “resident guests” and the national second-level protected animals goral. The “appearance rate” is also getting higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, director of the Wildlife and Wetland Protection Division of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Landscaping, introduced that the number of terrestrial spinal wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 species in 1994 to more than 500 now. The types and numbers of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years. .
The appearance of wild animals in cities is becoming more common, which is closely related to the continuous upgrade of the capital city’s greenery in recent years.
In particular, the new round of afforestation and greening of one million acres started in 2018, which proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological function of forest land and green space, and highlight the concept of “near nature”.
In the planning, we strive to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green areas, so that wild animals can “visit relatives and friends”. The trees planted are also honey and food plants that animals love.
Black soil “plants” agricultural modernization-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, July 26, report title: Black soil “plants” agricultural modernization
In midsummer, two spraying planes passed by the 10,000 mu high-yield demonstration field in the second operation station of the fifth management zone of Youyi Farm, forming two white lines. The green field was planted with black rice seedlings as the “first in the world” A few big characters are particularly eye-catching.
The station chief Kong Lingqiang said that this kind of aircraft can spray chemicals on more than 6,000 acres of cultivated land a day, and the efficiency is about 8 times that of drones and hundreds of times that of labor.
This farm is located in Youyi County, Heilongjiang Province, my country’s largest grain-producing province. From the sound of rice cutting in the past to the sound of rumbling motors in the past, traditional Chinese farming and farms have undergone transformation on this black soil belt.
In addition to airplanes, satellites are also used in the modern agricultural production of Youyi Farm.
Kong Lingqiang introduced that on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve precise fertilization, reduce agricultural input and reduce pollution; on the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the level of standardized farm machinery field operations.
During this year’s rice production process, the farm expanded the operating area of the satellite-navigation unmanned rice transplanting technology from 3,000 acres last year to 30,000 acres.
This technology makes the planting of seedlings more uniform, maximizes the use of sunlight and arable land resources, and saves 16 yuan in labor costs per mu.
The farm tried new technologies such as informatization and intelligence in agricultural production, and formed the largest agricultural machinery group in my country from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, the total number of agricultural machinery on the farm is 49,000 units (pieces), and the comprehensive field mechanization rate reaches 99.8%.
Agricultural machinery operations achieve 100% GPS satellite navigation, 100% precision seeding in dry fields, and 100% high-horsepower locomotive operations in dry fields.
“Green agriculture, smart agriculture, and digital agriculture are the path-finding directions for agricultural modernization.”
Said Liu Hualian, director of the Youyi Farm.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
In recent years, Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation, represented by farms, has played a leading role in the demonstration and leadership of modern large-scale agriculture “aircraft carrier”, and has initially established a modern agricultural industrial system dominated by large-scale planting, standardized production, and industrialized management.
In the suburbs of Youyi County, there is an Agricultural Machinery Expo Park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
More than 140 agricultural machinery and tools introduced and used by Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation over the years are exhibited here.
These agricultural machinery and farms have witnessed the development of my country’s agricultural modernization.
Home for everyone-the transfer of the masses in the Jiangkouhe Lake United polder, Hefei, Anhui Province-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26, title: Homecoming for everyone-the transfer of the masses in the Jiangkouhe Lake United polder, Hefei, Anhui Province
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu, Liu Xiacun
At around 4 pm on July 25, Fu Kunbao wore muddy rubber shoes and went from the front room to the back room, busy packing things back and forth with his wife Zhou Yan.
“After receiving a call from the village cadre to transfer, I was still stalking the grass in the field.”
Fu Kunbao said that he has transferred more than 60 acres of land and planted rice, and he is now growing well. “I took the medicine yesterday, and I haven’t cleaned all the tools.”
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner, “No one wants their home to be flooded, let’s leave a small home for everyone.”
In order to cope with the continued high water pressure and possible heavy rainfall in Chaohu Lake, Hefei City in Anhui Province is preparing to use the Jiangkouhe Lake United polder flood diversion storage facility where Fu Kunbao’s home is located on the 26th.
Jiangkouhe Lake United polder is located in Feixi County, next to the Chaohu Dike.
There are thousands of villagers involved in Yandian Township and Sanhe Township who need to be transferred.
As of 16:00 on the 25th, the water level of Chaohu Lake, my country’s fifth largest freshwater lake, remained at a high level of 13.2 meters, 0.7 meters above the guaranteed water level.
Fu Kunbao’s kitchen was clean and tidy. There was a pot of pumpkin head vegetables on the table, and there were eggs and some stewed vegetables in the refrigerator.
“I didn’t expect to move, the water in Jiangkou River looks good at the moment.”
Zhou Yan said that the house is a bungalow, and some large objects have not yet been decided where to put them.
“Clean up your valuables first. Large items such as refrigerators and TV sets can be temporarily placed at neighbors or relatives on high ground.”
Village leader Wang Liwen gave Fu Kunbao an idea.
Wang Liwen was responsible for the transfer and resettlement of 13 villagers, and notified each household to confirm the resettlement plan for each.
The nearest resettlement site to Fu Kunbao’s home is Su Xiao Primary School in Yandian Township, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to the big items, the more than 1,000 catties of food and some newly bought furniture were also a headache for Fu Kunbao and his wife.
“The food is going to be dragged to the relative’s house, and the furniture can’t be moved.”
The couple negotiated, put a stool under the newly bought bed, and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 o’clock in the afternoon, Fu Kunbao began to use a tricycle to transport things to his relatives’ home, and Zhou Yan continued to clean up at home.
After 11 o’clock in the evening, the couple looked around at home, turned on the switch, and prepared to go to the resettlement site.
“I hope the water will withdraw soon.”
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9:30 a.m. on July 26, the reporter saw at the Jiangkouhe Lake United polder site that the local area had made various preparations before flood diversion.
