China News Service, Hami, Xinjiang, July 26 Title: Xinjiang is deeply plowing the “sunflower field” and making good use of clean energy
More than 6000 pentagonal heliostats, each 48 square meters, are neatly arranged in circles, like a silver “sunflower field”, which rotates with the sun and reflects the sunlight to the 200-meter-high heat-absorbing tower in the center to realize power generation .
The reporter saw this scene on the 25th at the CLP Engineering Hami molten salt tower solar thermal power plant in Naomaohu Town, Yiwu County, Hami City, Xinjiang.
“The so-called molten salt tower solar thermal power generation is to concentrate sunlight through the mirror surface to the heat absorption tower to form heat energy, and then convert the heat energy into electrical energy through traditional power generation technology.”
Zhang Yong, deputy general manager of CLP Hami Solar Thermal Power Generation Co., Ltd., said that its design principle is similar to that of solar cookers used in rural areas in Northwest China, which must gather sunlight.
The power plant started construction in October 2017 and was connected to the grid at the end of last year. It covers an area of 6,600 mu and plans to install 14,500 heliostats.
“Compared with traditional solar power generation technology, its biggest advantage is that it can store the concentrated heat energy and generate electricity at night.”
Zhang Yong said that the 13-hour heat storage system configured in the project can keep the generator set in continuous and stable operation without being affected by changes in light; it can also quickly participate in grid peak shaving according to the demand of grid load peaks and valleys.
After the project is fully completed, it can achieve an annual power generation of 198 million kWh, save more than 60,000 tons of standard coal each year, reduce more than 60 tons of sulfur dioxide, more than 60 tons of nitrogen oxides, about 20 tons of dust, and more than 150,000 tons of carbon dioxide. Provide a steady stream of clean energy for the local area.
In addition, there is another silver “sunflower field” in the Shichengzi Photovoltaic Industrial Park in Hami City.
The Hami Fuguang Solar Photovoltaic Power Station covers an area of more than 2,300 acres. The 714 power generation equipment that has been built also follow the sun and always keep the sunlight at a 90-degree right angle to the surface of the concentrating panel.
“We use dual-axis tracking concentrating power generation technology. Through unified integrated control, all power generation equipment will adjust the angle according to the sun’s height to maintain power generation efficiency.”
Duan Mengqi, the station’s head, said that in good weather conditions, the power generation technology can increase the efficiency of conventional photovoltaic power generation by about 20%.
In the first half of this year, the power station has achieved power generation of more than 7 million kWh, supplementing local electricity demand.
Shichengzi Photovoltaic Industrial Park is currently a photovoltaic industry demonstration park with the largest monomer scale and the most complete types of photovoltaic modules in Xinjiang. There are 38 photovoltaic power generation projects in total, with a total installed capacity of 820,000 kilowatts.
The power generation completed in the first half of this year exceeded 110 million kWh, an increase of 6% over the same period in 2019.
Hami is one of the regions with the best solar energy resources in China.
The annual average total solar radiation is more than 6,200 megajoules per square meter, and the annual sunshine hours are about 3,200 hours.
In recent years, the city has vigorously developed the photovoltaic industry and planted “sunflower fields.”
A solar power generation scale with installed capacity of more than 2.5 million kilowatts has been built. In the first half of this year, the city’s photovoltaic power generation capacity exceeded 1.4 billion kWh, an increase of about 14% year-on-year.
Currently, there are more than 330 grid-connected photovoltaic power stations in Xinjiang, with an installed capacity of over 10 million kilowatts.
It is estimated that this year’s photovoltaic power generation will reach 15 billion kWh, which can replace more than 6 million tons of standard coal.
