Brazilian study shows that hydroxychloroquine is ineffective in the treatment of mild to moderate COVID-19
Recently, a Brazilian study showed that hydroxychloroquine is not effective for patients with mild to moderate COVID-19.
The research report was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
Pakistani researchers divided 667 patients from 55 hospitals across the country into three groups and conducted clinical trials; mainly compared the therapeutic effects of hydroxychloroquine alone or in combination with other antibiotics, azithromycin, and analyzed whether it would help to improve patients with mild and moderate COVID-19 ’S condition.
The results show that hydroxychloroquine not only has no therapeutic effect, but may have damaging side effects on organs.
This research was conducted by several authoritative hospitals in Brazil, such as Hospital Israelita Albert Einstein, Cardiology Hospital (HCor), Hospital Sírio-Libanês, etc. in collaboration with the Brazilian Clinical Research Institute (BCRI) and Brazil Critical Care Jointly completed by the Guardianship Research Network (BRICNet).
On the 25th local time, Brazilian President Bolsonaro announced through a social platform that the fourth COVID-19 test result was negative.
During the infection, Bolsonaro has been taking hydroxychloroquine and actively promoted it many times.
