Hao Yusheng, Chief Representative of Nasdaq China: Now is the best time for Chinese companies to go to the US for IPO-Economic Observer-Professional Financial News Website
Economic Observer reporter Zhang Bin. Because of the Ruixing Coffee fraud incident, the US market has imposed stricter supervision on China concept stocks. Coupled with the long-term pressure on valuations, Chinese concept stocks listed in the United States are under pressure. NetEase, JD.com, etc. Stocks have recently started their journey back to Hong Kong for listing.
Recently, Shell, Ideal Automobile and other companies have been enthusiastic about going public in the United States.
Under the epidemic and the China concept stock crisis, is now the best time for Chinese companies to go public in the United States?
“In terms of recent IPO cases and the situation of companies that are going to go public in the United States in the future, the IPOs going to the United States have not been affected in nature. On the contrary, the market is very good now. Even at this point in time, the most recent IPOs by Chinese companies in the United States have been Good time.”
Hao Yusheng, chief representative of the Nasdaq Stock Exchange in China, said at the “2020 Listed Company Leadership Summit China Stocks Branch” hosted by Xueqiu.
In April of this year, the United States Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) and the Public Company Accounting Regulatory Board (PCAOB) issued the “Statement on the Important Role of Audit Quality and Supervision in Obtaining Audit and Other International Information — Regarding the current Discussion on the Challenges of Information Access.
The statement stated that although international cooperation and coordination have increased significantly in recent years, the US regulatory authorities still have problems with access to information, and the SEC and PCAOB still face legal and practical challenges. Corresponding to this document is the PCAOB website. A detailed list of listed companies that have encountered audit obstacles and their audit institutions, including a large number of Chinese concept stock companies.
In addition, in May of this year, the US Senate passed the “Foreign Companies Accountability Act,” imposing additional information disclosure requirements for foreign companies to list in the United States.
In Hao Yusheng’s view, the Chinese concept stock crisis has not affected investors’ appetite.
“When this news first came out, everyone panicked. Everyone asked if they could go public in the United States in the future. But then we discovered that these problems were not a problem on the investor side. Investors had a recent roadshow to the US for an IPO. These questions may be asked, and even become standardized questions, but they are not regarded by investors as an important factor in investing or not investing in a Chinese company.
It is recommended that everyone treat the current situation with a calm mind as much as possible.
Of course, this may seem to be the worst situation in the past two years, but as far as investors’ appetite is concerned, it has not been affected in any way.
So from now until the end of this year or before the US general election, the upsurge of going to the US for IPOs will continue. “
On May 9 this year, Kingsoft Cloud officially went public on the Nasdaq in the United States, becoming the first Chinese company to go to the United States for an IPO after the epidemic.
“The listing of Kingsoft Cloud gives Chinese companies preparing for an IPO very much confidence.”
Hao Yusheng said.
Xueqiu’s report on China’s stocks in the first half of 2020 shows that in the first half of this year, a total of 20 Chinese companies went to the US for IPOs, an increase of 17.6% over the same period last year; from the perspective of total initial fundraising, 20 companies raised a total of 2.725 billion. Compared with the same period last year, it has rebounded, up by more than 52.4%. In terms of industry distribution, the number of IPOs in the healthcare industry in the first half of this year was outstanding, an increase of 100% over the same period last year.
According to Hao Yusheng, the quality of Chinese companies that went to the US for IPO in the first half of this year is relatively high, and high-quality companies with strong fundamentals and growth potential will be more favored by investors.
In the short, medium and long term, Hao Yusheng continues to be optimistic about Ming Chinese companies’ IPO in the United States.
“In the short term, the upsurge of going to the US for IPOs continues; in the medium term, Chinese companies have more choices. A-shares, Hong Kong stocks, and US stocks. Everyone will consider the US election and Sino-US relations as market choices and timing considerations. In the long run, Everything will return to normal. Market fluctuations are cycles. There are political cycles and economic cycles, and they will eventually return to the normal stage. The stock market has always moved forward with volatility.”
Hao Yusheng also said, “There are many uncertain factors this year, but for high-quality companies, no matter whether the market is good or bad, as long as they are solid and have growth that investors can see, other factors are relatively minor. Yes, investors need to invest in outstanding Chinese companies.”
