Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to be smashed while playing in the university playground.
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, and the child was compensated before suing the school
Correspondent Zhao Yifan
The 3-year-old Xiaowen was accidentally hit in the head by Chen from the softball team while playing on the playground of a certain university.
After Chen made compensation, Xiaowen’s father, Mr. Wen, served as Xiaowen’s legal representative and sued the school to the court, demanding an apology from the school where the incident occurred, as well as payment of medical expenses and mental damage relief for a total of 20,000 yuan.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Haidian District People’s Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net on the playground at the time of the incident, and that it had fulfilled its proper safety guarantee obligations, and Chen had already paid compensation. Based on this judgment, the plaintiff’s decision was rejected. Claims.
Mr. Wen alleged that he took Xiaowen to play on the school playground during the summer vacation of 2019, when the softball team was training on the playground.
In order to avoid the risks posed by this, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents play in safe areas designated by the softball team.
But then the softball player Chen dropped his hand while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the guard net into the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiaowen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that school stadium facilities do not meet the relevant safety requirements, and not on the team with customs facilities for effective management.
The school’s negligence caused the above incident to occur, which caused Xiaowen to suffer tremendous physical and mental pain, and at the same time brought greater pain to his family. The school should bear legal responsibility for this.
In this regard, the school argued that the school has set up a protective net on the playground, and posted management regulations and training notices, informing them that entering the playground must maintain a safe distance from the training site and reminding their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school was “not enough.” Obligation of safety protection", so I do not agree to compensation.
After the trial, the court held that the site involved in the incident was a site open to the public for free by the university involved. Although the school has a safety guarantee obligation for the management of the playground, this safety guarantee obligation only needs to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net on the playground, and has fulfilled its proper safety guarantee obligations, and Chen also compensated Xiaowen for various losses including medical expenses and transportation expenses in accordance with the previously reached compensation agreement for more than two thousand yuan. It is agreed that this dispute will be resolved at one time.
After the incident, Xiaowen’s parents again claimed compensation from the school. There was no basis in the law, and the court ruled that all of the plaintiff’s claims were rejected.
After the verdict was pronounced, neither party appealed, and the verdict is now effective.
According to Article 37 of my country’s Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation to guarantee safety; in the event that the actions of a third party cause damage to others, the third party bears tort liability, but the safety guarantee is not fulfilled. The responsible public place manager shall bear corresponding supplementary responsibilities.
The judge said that as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the entire place and foresee possible dangers and damages, so that he is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or reduce the extent of damage, and to avoid and mitigate The cost of damage is the lowest, so the law stipulates that it shall bear the corresponding guarantee obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified people entering the playground that is free to the public, the school’s safety guarantee obligations should be compatible with the social activities it engages in. Specifically, it should take basic safety measures and deal with hidden dangers. Have the obligation to inform.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety guarantee obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has adopted a protective net and fulfilled its obligation of notification, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for third-party infringements, even if the administrators of public places such as schools fail to fulfill their obligations to ensure safety, their liability is a supplement to compensation for damages. According to the latest civil code, after the administrators assume supplementary responsibilities, You can also claim compensation from a third party.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victims should not expand the scope of compensation after they have received compensation from the direct infringer.
