Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated epidemics
In the early stage of the outbreak of the COVID-19, Israel’s prevention and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of the ban on prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Israel has recently increased significantly. The Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of COVID-19 was confirmed in Israel. It quickly closed all entry and exit ports, suspended non-essential industries, schools changed to online teaching, restricted public transportation and non-essential social activities, and blocked cities with severe epidemics. The military and police jointly maintain prevention and control measures, etc.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results. By mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Israel fell back to single digits in a single day.
As the epidemic is brought under control, Israel’s various prevention and control measures have been fully unblocked. Since June, the number of newly diagnosed COVID-19 has gradually rebounded.
Especially since July, the spread of the epidemic has continued to accelerate.
In recent days, there are more than 1,500 new cases in Israel every day for 8 days. As of the time of publication on July 25, there were 916 new cases on that day.
As of July 25, there have been 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
Facing the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed public entertainment venues such as gymnasiums, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs, and introduced a public transportation restriction policy, stipulating that the number of passengers per bus cannot exceed 20 people. .
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictive measures, including the implementation of “closure of the city” on weekends, etc., stipulating that the “closure of the city” shall be implemented from 17:00 every Friday to 5:00 every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but shops, shopping centers, barber shops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while supermarkets, pharmacies and other basic services will remain open .
At the same time, on all dates and time periods, gatherings of more than 10 people are forbidden, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes are forbidden to eat in, and only takeaway services are allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people did not pay enough attention to the severity of the epidemic and failed to form a joint force with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After the recurrence of the Israeli epidemic, many people took to the streets to protest and march because the government’s prevention and control measures affected their economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, believing that the anti-epidemic policy would affect the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu’s residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu’s promulgation of prevention and control measures such as the prohibition of restaurants and cafes without giving corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people fail to observe the regulations on wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters during outdoor activities. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing a mask, many people only wear the mask on their chin or on their wrists.
During the recurrence of the epidemic, the school was the hardest hit area for the spread of the COVID-19 virus. According to a reporter’s recent visit to this kindergarten, it was discovered that neither the teachers nor students in the kindergarten had worn masks as required by the government, nor had they maintained a safe social distance of two meters from each other. Infection with the virus lays down hidden dangers.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the Israeli National Security Council’s expert advisory group to combat the epidemic, believes that Israel is moving towards a “dangerous situation” and pointed out that Israel’s current epidemic prevention and control measures are not enough, and all leisure and entertainment venues and summer vacations should be closed. Schools to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to fight the epidemic. The parliament and government departments should abandon their own interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on the fight against the epidemic, and formulate clear steps that include relevant restrictions on different departments.
