At Balong Zhuokang sentry point, platoon leader Yu Wang and a soldier stand guard.
In this place where the annual average temperature is more than ten degrees below zero, a row of simple barracks stands on the mountain pass. Not far from the barracks, a national flag is fluttering in the wind. The soldiers are on duty in the wind every day, and they need to regularly patrol higher altitudes. .
The soldiers climbed up the steep slope of the rubble, requiring both hands and feet.
It was late July, when the flowers and plants flourished in low-altitude areas, and in Ba Nong Zhuo Kang, only the ravine behind the barracks had relatively dense green.
Gao Peng, a soldier who has been stationed at the outpost for 6 years, pointed to the ravine and said that this is their back garden. Only in July and August each year can the grass grow slowly. After a while, all of them turned yellow and covered with snow.
Patrol on foot may take about 9 hours.
In the harsh plateau environment, the soldiers stationed here are accompanied by snow-capped mountains and glaciers all year round, and they regularly patrol higher mountain passes.
A few days ago, a patrol team composed of eight fighters, led by the instructor Liang Yixin, once again embarked on the patrol road.
Each soldier carries a weight of about 30 kilograms and marches towards the target point early in the morning.
On the way, a soldier fought back, and his comrades gave emergency help.
In addition to patrol missions, the soldiers at the Ba Nong Chokang outpost have to conduct tactical and physical training every day.
Time passed by, the altitude was rising, the oxygen content was getting lower and lower, and the physical strength was constantly being overdrawn. These factors tested the will of the patrol team members.
They gritted their teeth and insisted, stepping over several landslides and several distressed beaches one after another.
At about 16 o’clock, it was lunch time for the patrol members. They took out their own dry food and sat on the spot at an altitude of more than 5,700 meters, accompanied by sleet, and supplemented their physical strength with food.
The soldiers at the Ba Nong Chokang sentry point conducted tactical and physical training.
During the break, they would play cards together, and losers would do push-ups, both for entertainment and physical exercise.
After a short rest in the cold wind, they climbed to the target point of the patrol, took out the national flag on the mountain pass, and solemnly swore.
Behind them is the snow-capped mountains, and in front of them are dozens of kilometers of no man’s land. They are the safest guardians of the country.
